[Since this disease is in horses there is definitely minuscule chance of it
being foot and mouth disease. The high level of concern for any vesicular
disease is always that it might be foot and mouth disease. If FMD were
introduced in the U.S would cost some 1 billion dollars in the first year
alone. There has been great progress eradicating this disease in South
America. Introduction in places like Argentina, Chile or the historically
free regions of Central America would indeed be very costly. The fourth
vesicular disease of domestic animals not mentioned in these posting is
swine vesicular disease. The viral agents associated with these diseases
are not closely related but the clinical symptoms are indistinguishable in
susceptible species and can only be definitively diagnosed with laboratory
investigations. - Mod.PC
[2
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 08:58:30 -0600
From: Cristobal Andres Zepeda Sein <czepeda@ns1.oirsa.org.sv>

Dr. Donoghue wrote "Horses presented with oral ulcerations could have
vesicular stomatitis, foot and mouth disease or vesicular exanthema, but
not equine herpes. Any of these could have serious repercussions in New
Zealand!"
Horses may indeed get vesicular stomatitis but are definitely not affected
by FMD. Only experimental infection with some strains vesicular exanthema
of swine virus has led to disease in horses (Blood and Henderson).
Many ProMED-mail subscribers are not formally trained in medical subjects.
Messages like this one may lead to false conceptions. I strongly suggest
either editing or comment from the moderators prior to posting.
ProMED-mail is the greatest thing that has happened lately, but as the number
of participants increase it is becoming more difficult to distinguish
facts from fiction.
--
